properties.description: St James's Piccadilly is a Grade I listed Christopher Wren church in the heart of the West End. Completed in 1684, and known as the Artists' Church, its interiors include historic works of art by Grinling Gibbons (reredos, organ case and font), postwar Classical interiors by Albert Richardson, and contemporary art by Che Lovelace honouring the 18th-century abolitionist Quobna Ottobah Cugoano.

images.title: St James's Church Piccadilly, seen from Jermyn Street
The lime wood reredos carved by Grinling Gibbons
The River (left) and Passage (right) by Che Lovelace hanging in the narthex at St James's Piccadilly

properties.name: St James's Piccadilly

properties.description: Manbey Pod is a charming and functional garden studio located in East London, designed by Studio Bark to provide a family amenity space, storage area, and textile studio. It was self-built by the home-owners, Peter and Joan, using Studio Bark's revolutionary U-Build construction system; manufactured off-site as a kit of parts and built by Peter and Joan in their garden.
properties.name: Manbey Pod

properties.description: A full refurbishment of a 1950 end-of-terrace house with a new timber annex. The ground floor space flows from the living area to the garden, integrating new dining and kitchen areas. The project focused on customising components. Timber foundation beams, posts, and a plywood waffle slab were digitally fabricated, reducing embodied CO2 by 70% compared to brick and concrete foundations.
properties.name: Wooden Annex

properties.description: Winner of the 2024 'Don't Move Improve' award for best project under £100k A self build 38m2 triangular micro home converted from a former mechanic's garage,  creating a flexible and multifunctional home fit for living and working in.  Come and see sliding beds, triangular sofas and a pocket garden.

images.title: Street view of the Triangle House - a converted mechanic's garage
Triangle House: Winner of the 2024 'Don't Move, Improve!' prize for best project under 100k
Inverted bay window filled with bamboo creates privacy and 'defensible space'  from the street
Aerial view of the Triangle House
Multifunctional bedroom and living space overlooking a private courtyard

properties.name: Don't Move, Improve! - Triangle House

properties.description:
Join Martin Glover,  Deaf BSL user, architect and art facilitator, on a guided tour of The Line, East London's public art trail. Martin will lead you around the Greenwich Peninsula section of The Line, introducing you to installations by Alex Chinneck, Serge Attukwei Clottey & Antony Gormley & more.

The route is wheelchair-accessible and there will be only BSL interpretation, no spoken English.
properties.name: BSL Walking Tour of The Line

properties.description: London is the world's first National Park City, and our visitors centre at 109 Fleet Street is the entry point to hundreds of places to visit and things to do across a greener, healthier and wilder London.

images.title: London National Park City visitors centre at 109 Fleet Street looking towards St Paul's Cathedral

properties.name: London National Park City Visitors Centre

properties.description: Incredible transformation of a Victorian end of terrace with multiple extensions at the rear, side and top transforming it into a beautiful contemporary home, with a nudge to the traditional. Inside is a veritable jungle!

images.title: Looking up the double height greenhouse enclosed courtyard
Street view of the house and the extensions
A glimpse of the views and the light through the house, from front to garden
Looking at the new rear of the building

properties.name: 69 Adys Road

properties.description: Winner of the Environmental Leadership Prize in the 2024 Don't Move Improve Awards, House Made by Many Hands is the first building structure in the UK to specify low-carbon LC3 concrete, together with hand-cast hempcrete walls, a hardwood frame in place of traditional steel, natural materials throughout and a rigorous policy of reuse and recycling for the interior.

Hempcrete wall in kitchen area.

Photo by James Retief

Photo by James Retief

properties.name: Don't Move, Improve! - House Made by Many Hands

properties.description:
Founded by Peter Layton in 1976, London Glassblowing is among Europe’s foremost glass art galleries and one of the longest running hot glass studios. 

The exquisite glass art on display in the gallery is constantly changing. Visitors can not only view pieces from the UK’s finest studio glass artists, but can also watch them practise their craft in the studio that lies beyond its white walls.

images.title: Bruce Marks, Studio Manager (Photograph by Joshua Bratt)
Studio team in action (Photograph by Edmund White)
Image of the gallery by Alick Cotterill

properties.name: London Glassblowing

properties.description: Discover Hackney’s exemplary contemporary residential projects on this inspiring walk through the Broadway Market and Graham Road & Mapledene conservation areas led by Hidden House Project. Explore how these projects' thoughtful design and development contribute positively to the public realm and the architectural diversity and richness of the area, shaping London Fields' future heritage.

images.title: Photo by Hidden House Project - London Fields, E8
Photo by Hidden House Project - Broadway Market, London Fields, E8
Photo by Hidden House Project - London Fields, E8

properties.name: Future Heritage: Contemporary Architecture in Hackney

properties.description: thinkFOUND make socially and environmentally sustainable furniture. We represent a social value model that gives back to communities around London. From our workshop in the Argall Industrial Estate we incorporate carpentry, fabrication, upcycling, training, employment, coaching and more. Over the weekend we will be hosting an open studio demonstrating our processes and showcasing past work.
properties.name: thinkFOUND

properties.description:
This walking tour explores the feminist history of Hampstead Garden Suburb.  Learn about how the planning and architecture of the Suburb, founded by Henrietta Barnet during the Women's Suffrage movement, was influenced by feminist social values. 

3 of 3 walks run by the Hampstead Garden Suburb Trust.
properties.name: Women of Hampstead Garden Suburb

properties.description:
Welcome to Open House Festival 2024 at Wolves Lane Horticulture Centre ! Join us for a captivating exploration of urban food production and sustainable living. Discover our unique blend of historic glasshouse structures from the 1970s alongside our new cutting-edge sustainable 
buildings designed by Studio Gil and Material Cultures.  Tour and experience the beauty and purpose of Wolves Lane.
properties.name: Wolves Lane Centre

properties.description: Discover Soho in the 1700s and 1800s - a place of bawdy houses, body snatchers and benevolent doctors who rubbed along together in alleyways and elegant townhouses. Soho’s narrow streets have been blighted by cholera and seen some of the country’s first specialist hospitals. Many of its buildings escaped the bombing of WWll and at least in part can be seen today.

images.title: Lou talking outside the Hospital for Women in Soho Square
The Broad Street pump responsible for the 1854 Soho cholera outbreak
Mary Seacole's home after the Crimean War

properties.name: Death, debauchery and doctors in Soho

properties.description: An overhaul and extension of a Victorian House near Nunhead Cemetery
properties.name: Nunhead Cemetery House

properties.description: We are a 12-acre organic food-growing workers' cooperative, located on the edge of Epping Forest. We grow food that is delivered throughout Waltham Forest by our fruit and veg subscription service, hold volunteering and run courses. Our open days are a rare opportunity to experience the site on the weekend.
properties.name: OrganicLea Community Growers Open Day

properties.description: A radical energy reduction transformation of a 1920s home that adds a light-filled basement arranged around an atrium with living wall.

images.title: Twyford Avenue - rear - photo - Kilian O'Sullivan
Twyford Avenue - atrium - photo - Kilian O'Sullivan
Twyford Avenue - atrium - photo - Kilian O'Sullivan

properties.name: 62 Twyford Avenue

properties.description:
Enfield Council has been awarded grant funding from the National Heritage Lottery Fund, The Pilgrim Trust and The Enfield Society to understand how the non-conformist chapel in Lavender Hill Cemetery can be conserved and identify potential new uses.

Join us to explore the cemetery, take a look inside the former Chapel and give us your thoughts on its future!

images.title: Interior image of Lavender Hill Non-Conformist Chapel

properties.name: Lavender Hill: Chapel and Community

properties.description: Oru Sutton is a landmark workspace, leisure, and destination space in the heart of Sutton High Street, creating a nurturing environment for people to connect and thrive in their work and personal lives.
properties.name: Oru Space

properties.description:
The Trampery Wood Green is host to 50 artists currently occupying studios in the building. At our open day event you will have the opportunity to come and see their work and their workspaces!
As part of the open day we will activate the space by hosting multiple activities in the lounge throughout the event. For this we are planning on having an agenda of skill-sharing, music and food and drinks.
properties.name: The Trampery Wood Green

properties.description: This two-hour walk covers a number of leading personalities who led the fight back against the Axis Powers, explores preparations for some of the most decisive battles, considers how London became the centre of the free world while not losing sight of how people got on with their lives. This is realised by visiting the locations they worked from or the memorials raised to them.

images.title: Admiralty Citadel - the World War II bunker in the heart of St James's

properties.name: World War 2 in Westminster - a walk

properties.description: Join this walking tour to discover how post-war architects and planners re-imagined the future of housing, including the low-rise Alexandra and Ainsworth Estate designed by Neave Brown and the high-rise monolith Trellick Tower by  Erno Goldfinger. This walk is not about housing pre-fixed by ‘public’, ‘social’, ‘council’ or ‘local’ – but the concept of housing itself.
properties.name: A tale of two cities - two takes on modernist housing

properties.description: In centuries past thousands of people thronged to Oxford Street to watch executions – now London's most famous destination draws millions of visitors who spend millions of pounds in Europe's busiest shopping thoroughfare. This walk uses the built environment to chart the history of retail and witness its future already in action.

images.title: Centrepoint: completed 1966. Described by Pevsner as "coarse in the extreme" but now Grade II listed

properties.name: Oxford Street walking tour – past, present and future

properties.description: The owners of this Victorian house had a dilemma. Should they relocate to Australia or stay in London? Mulroy Architects design combines both with a series of bold design interventions include moving the staircase from the centre to the side of the house, a full-plan basement and a new 9.3 metre diagonal extension, and large openable roof lights that capture the south facing light.
properties.name: 59 Mountview Road

properties.description: Up in Smoke - the NOW Gallery Design Commission by artist John Booth and architecture studio CAN, transforms the gallery into a vibrant installation that reveals the rich history of Greenwich Peninsula, through its iconic chimneys. The exhibition combines the duo's distinctive styles: Booth's playful, colourful design aesthetic and CAN's fresh, irreverent approach to architecture.
properties.name: Up in Smoke by John Booth X CAN

properties.description: Join curator William Rees for a tour of sites in Southall with ties to the Martinware collection; from the location of the Martin brothers' studio on the Grand Union Canal, to the lost fountain of Southall Manor House Grounds, to the home of the collection today at Southall Library, Dominion Centre. Participants will get a free Martinware map and view collection items recently placed on view.
properties.name: Martinware Trail in Southall

properties.description: Once a Victorian arboretum, Abney Park Cemetery, part of London's Magnificent Seven, was revitalised with National Heritage Lottery funding in 2021. The renovation restored the chapel and main entrance, creating a vibrant workshop space for London-based art and design collective, WAX Atelier. During Open House, WAX Atelier will showcase innovative projects in their unique workspace amidst the park

images.title: WAX Atelier's Materials Lab at Abney Park
CQ Studio's Material Lab at Abney Park

properties.name: WAX Atelier within Abney Park

properties.description: St John the Evangelist, Palmers Green, is a prominent landmark on Green Lanes, the church was designed by John Oldrid Scott and was built 1903-1909. There is a wealth of post first world war Morris & Co glass, the east window by J.H. Dearle being particularly striking. There are more recent windows by Godard & Gibbs and a notable one of 1918 by Frank Salisbury.
properties.name: Façades a new piece by Brigitte Beraha

properties.description: Gordon Hill Pillbox and anti-tank ‘dragon’s teeth’ are one of the few remaining examples of World War II defences that once surrounded London, built to defend against an expected German invasion in 1940. Artist Joe Robinson of Snapshot Heritage, and John Cole of The Enfield Society, are hosting a drop-in day looking at Pillbox and early war in Enfield.
properties.name: Gordon Hill Station Wartime Pillbox and Dragon’s Teeth

properties.description: The team behind the Swing Bridge will describe its inception, evolution, and construction process and how a community deepened their relationship with this pivotal structure that bridges old and new. Palaeontologists and geologists who have researched the site in detail will take you on a behind-the-scenes tour of the constructed outcrops that give the Deep Time narrative to the CP Dinosaurs.
properties.name: Dinosaur Swing Bridge in Crystal Palace Park

properties.description: Join a City Guide to explore the stories of queer monarchs; the Cathedral convenience; erotic theatre; cross-dressers and find out what Henry VIII had to do with it all.
properties.name: From Prejudice to Pride

properties.description: It began with wool and ended in wildness. This tour with a City Guide will uncover 800 years of history and happenings associated with the incident-packed Bartholomew Fair.
properties.name: Bartholomew Fair

properties.description: Home to Unagru Architecture Urbanism and DEDRAFT studio, the new cooperative space strives to nurture collaboration alongside other built environment professionals. In this street-facing space in Hackney Downs, we sought to fit out the spaces economically and sustainably as possible, with low carbon, #nomoregas initiative and reused material strategies, while embracing a bold use of colour.

images.title: Unagru/Dedraft/Diagonal A collaborative work space in Hackney Downs

properties.name: Diagonal/A Architecture Studio

properties.description:
London is the ultimate urban sprawl. But hiding among the buildings and cars there are an estimated eight million trees. So who else do we share our city with? Do you have a neighbourhood goose? Are there really seals in the River Thames? 

Join Lucy Brown from wildlife conservation charity ZSL on a journey through London's wild alter-ego, via the parks and waterways of Camden and Westminster.

images.title:

properties.name: Beaks and Boroughs: nature in London

properties.description: Join a captivating journey through the City of London with our exclusive Muslim Heritage Tour. Discover the deep connections of Salahuddin Ayubi and marvel at the UK's oldest Muslim statues, dating back 1000 years. Uncover the legacy of England’s most famous Middle Eastern immigrant and delve into fascinating tales of crime and health in history.
properties.name: Muslim Heritage of the City tour

properties.description: Tree Courtyard House is a newly completed two-bedroom house in the heart of Walthamstow Village designed by RIBA award-winning architects ao–ft. The peaceful single-story home is arranged around a secluded courtyard, and is a standard-setting example of using CLT construction to craft a sustainable, adaptable home.

images.title: ao–ft's Tree Courtyard House, photograph by Rory Gardiner

properties.name: Tree Courtyard House

properties.description: Formed of a series of brick volumes set on the centre of a quiet backland site, 31/44 Architects completed a new-build family home that is deceptively open and light inside its strong masonry exterior. The mass echoes the informal backs of adjacent houses and begins to express the internal layout, where different height spaces lend hierarchy to the principal rooms.

images.title: Exterior context, photograph by Anna Stathaki

properties.name: Park House

properties.description: Southall Manor House is a Grade II* Listed Tudor building - the oldest building in Southall and potentially one of the oldest surviving buildings in West London. The building underwent recent refurbishment, extension and landscaping from 00 Architects. For Open House, the building's heritage will be animated by scents from perfumers 420Tuesdays and Kushbu.
properties.name: Southall Manor House

properties.description:
Two triple-level apartments or townhouses close to London Fields Lido.
The homes are clad in red/brown zinc above a street level base storey of recycled bricks.
The homes interlock in section to optimise views and sunlight while stepping away from neighbours.
properties.name: London Fields West
